				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Qua=
drilateral with two pairs of parallel sides</div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">This article=
 is about the quadrilateral. For the music album, see <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallelograms_(album)" title=3D"Parallelograms (album)=
">Parallelograms (album)</a>.</div>
<div class=3D"skin-invert-image"><table class=3D"infobox"><tbody><tr><th co=
lspan=3D"2" class=3D"infobox-above" style=3D"background:#e7dcc3; color:inhe=
rit;">Parallelogram</th></tr><tr><td colspan=3D"2" class=3D"infobox-image">=
<span typeof=3D"mw:File"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Para=
llelogram.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wik=
imedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/41/Parallelogram.svg/250px-Parallelogr=
am.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"220" height=3D"151" class=3D"mw-fil=
e-element" data-file-width=3D"255" data-file-height=3D"175"></a></span><div=
 class=3D"infobox-caption">This parallelogram is a rhomboid as it has unequ=
al sides and no right angles.</div></td></tr><tr><th scope=3D"row" class=3D=
"infobox-label">Type</th><td class=3D"infobox-data"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Quadrilateral" title=3D"Quadrilateral">Quadrilateral</a>,=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid" title=3D"Trapezoid">Tr=
apezium</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=3D"row" class=3D"infobox-label"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edge_(geometry)" title=3D"Edge (geometry)=
">Edges</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vertex_(geometry)"=
 title=3D"Vertex (geometry)">vertices</a></th><td class=3D"infobox-data">4<=
/td></tr><tr><th scope=3D"row" class=3D"infobox-label"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_planar_symmetry_groups" title=3D"List of plana=
r symmetry groups">Symmetry group</a></th><td class=3D"infobox-data"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Point_reflection" title=3D"Point reflect=
ion">C<sub>2</sub></a>, [2]<sup>+</sup>,</td></tr><tr><th scope=3D"row" cla=
ss=3D"infobox-label"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area" title=
=3D"Area">Area</a></th><td class=3D"infobox-data"><i>bh</i> (base =C3=97 he=
ight);<br><i>ab</i> sin <i>=CE=B8</i> (product of adjacent sides and sine o=
f the vertex angle determined by them)</td></tr><tr><th scope=3D"row" class=
=3D"infobox-label">Properties</th><td class=3D"infobox-data"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convex_polygon" title=3D"Convex polygon">Convex =
polygon</a></td></tr></tbody></table></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_geometry" title=3D=
"Euclidean geometry">Euclidean geometry</a>, a <b>parallelogram</b> is a <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simple_polygon" title=3D"Simple poly=
gon">simple</a> (non-<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_self-=
intersecting_polygons" title=3D"List of self-intersecting polygons">self-in=
tersecting</a>) <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadrilateral" tit=
le=3D"Quadrilateral">quadrilateral</a> with two pairs of <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallel_(geometry)" title=3D"Parallel (geometry)">p=
arallel</a> sides. The opposite or facing sides of a parallelogram are of e=
qual length and the opposite angles of a parallelogram are of equal measure=
. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Congruence_(geometry)" title=
=3D"Congruence (geometry)">congruence</a> of opposite sides and opposite an=
gles is a direct consequence of the Euclidean <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Parallel_postulate" title=3D"Parallel postulate">parallel postu=
late</a> and neither condition can be proven without appealing to the Eucli=
dean parallel postulate or one of its equivalent formulations.
</p><p>By comparison, a quadrilateral with at least one pair of parallel si=
des is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid" title=3D"Trape=
zoid">trapezoid</a> in American English or a trapezium in British English.
</p><p>The three-dimensional counterpart of a parallelogram is a <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallelepiped" title=3D"Parallelepiped">par=
allelepiped</a>.
</p><p>The word "parallelogram" comes from the Greek =CF=80=CE=B1=CF=81=CE=
=B1=CE=BB=CE=BB=CE=B7=CE=BB=CF=8C-=CE=B3=CF=81=CE=B1=CE=BC=CE=BC=CE=BF=CE=
=BD, <i>parall=C4=93l=C3=B3-grammon</i>, which means "a shape of parallel l=
ines".
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Special_cases">Special case=
s</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DParallelog=
ram&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Special cases=
"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></spa=
n></div>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rectangle" title=3D"Rectan=
gle">Rectangle</a> =E2=80=93 A parallelogram with four right angles.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhombus" title=3D"Rhombus">Rho=
mbus</a> =E2=80=93 A parallelogram with four sides of equal length.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square_(geometry)" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Square (geometry)">Square</a> =E2=80=93 A parallelogram=
 with four sides of equal length and four right angles.</li>
<li>Rhomboid =E2=80=93 A parallelogram with adjacent sides that are of uneq=
ual lengths and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angle#Types_of_ang=
les" title=3D"Angle">non-right angles</a> (and thus is neither a rectangle =
nor a rhombus). This term is not used in modern mathematics but it does sur=
vive in some contexts in biology in names like the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Rhomboid_muscles" title=3D"Rhomboid muscles">rhomboid musc=
les</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glossary_of_leaf_morpho=
logy#Leaf_and_leaflet_shapes" title=3D"Glossary of leaf morphology">rhomboi=
d leaf shapes</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallelogram#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Characterizations">Characte=
rizations</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPa=
rallelogram&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Chara=
cterizations"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]=
</span></span></div>
<p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simple_polygon" title=3D"Simp=
le polygon">simple</a> (non-self-intersecting) <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Quadrilateral" title=3D"Quadrilateral">quadrilateral</a> is a =
parallelogram <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/If_and_only_if" titl=
e=3D"If and only if">if and only if</a> any one of the following statements=
 is true:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Parallelogram#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallelogr=
am#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>Two pairs of opposite sides are parallel (by definition).</li>
<li>Two pairs of opposite sides are equal in length.</li>
<li>Two pairs of opposite angles are equal in measure.</li>
<li>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diagonal" title=3D"Diagona=
l">diagonals</a> bisect each other.</li>
<li>One pair of opposite sides is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Parallel_(geometry)" title=3D"Parallel (geometry)">parallel</a> and equal i=
n length.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adjacent_angles" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Adjacent angles">Adjacent angles</a> are <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supplementary_angles" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Supplementary angles">supplementary</a>.</li>
<li>Each diagonal divides the quadrilateral into two <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Congruence_(geometry)" title=3D"Congruence (geometry)">c=
ongruent</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triangle" title=3D"Tr=
iangle">triangles</a>.</li>
<li>The sum of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square_number" =
title=3D"Square number">squares</a> of the sides equals the sum of the squa=
res of the diagonals. (This is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Parallelogram_law" title=3D"Parallelogram law">parallelogram law</a>.)</li=
>
<li>It has <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rotational_symmetry" ti=
tle=3D"Rotational symmetry">rotational symmetry</a> of order 2.</li>
<li>The sum of the distances from any interior point to the sides is indepe=
ndent of the location of the point.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallelogram#cite_note-4"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> (This is an extension of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vi=
viani%27s_theorem" title=3D"Viviani's theorem">Viviani's theorem</a>.)</li>
<li>There is a point <i>X</i> in the plane of the quadrilateral with the pr=
operty that every straight line through <i>X</i> divides the quadrilateral =
into two regions of equal area.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallelogram#cite_note-5"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p></li></ul>
<p>Thus, all parallelograms have all the properties listed above, and <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Converse_(logic)" title=3D"Converse (lo=
gic)">conversely</a>, if just any one of these statements is true in a simp=
le quadrilateral, then it is considered a parallelogram.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Other_properties">Other pro=
perties</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPara=
llelogram&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Other p=
roperties"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</s=
pan></span></div>
<ul><li>Opposite sides of a parallelogram are parallel (by definition) and =
so will never intersect.</li>
<li>The area of a parallelogram is twice the area of a triangle created by =
one of its diagonals.</li>
<li>The area of a parallelogram is also equal to the magnitude of the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_cross_product" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Vector cross product">vector cross product</a> of two <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adjacent_side_(polygon)" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Adjacent side (polygon)">adjacent</a> sides.</li>
<li>Any line through the midpoint of a parallelogram bisects the area.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Parallelogram#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>Any non-degenerate <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Affine_tran=
sformation" title=3D"Affine transformation">affine transformation</a> takes=
 a parallelogram to another parallelogram.</li>
<li>A parallelogram has <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rotational=
_symmetry" title=3D"Rotational symmetry">rotational symmetry</a> of order 2=
 (through 180=C2=B0) (or order 4 if a square). If it also has exactly two l=
ines of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reflectional_symmetry" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Reflectional symmetry">reflectional symmetry</a=
> then it must be a rhombus or an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Oblong" class=3D"mw-disambig" title=3D"Oblong">oblong</a> (a non-square rec=
tangle). If it has four lines of reflectional symmetry, it is a <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square" title=3D"Square">square</a>.</li>
<li>The perimeter of a parallelogram is 2(<i>a</i> + <i>b</i>) where <i>a</=
i> and <i>b</i> are the lengths of adjacent sides.</li>
<li>Unlike any other convex polygon, a parallelogram cannot be inscribed in=
 any triangle with less than twice its area.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallelogram#cite_not=
e-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup></li>
<li>The centers of four squares all constructed either internally or extern=
ally on the sides of a parallelogram are the vertices of a square.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Weisstein_8-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Parallelogram#cite_note-Weisstein-8"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>If two lines parallel to sides of a parallelogram are constructed <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Concurrent_lines" title=3D"Concurrent l=
ines">concurrent</a> to a diagonal, then the parallelograms formed on oppos=
ite sides of that diagonal are equal in area.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Weisstein_=
8-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallelo=
gram#cite_note-Weisstein-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>The diagonals of a parallelogram divide it into four triangles of equal=
 area.</li></ul>
