<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Parallelograms_arising_from=
_other_figures">Parallelograms arising from other figures</h2><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DParallelogram&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Parallelograms arising from=
 other figures"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Automedian_triangle">Autome=
dian triangle</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DParallelogram&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: =
Automedian triangle"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bra=
cket">]</span></span></div>
<p>An <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automedian_triangle" title=
=3D"Automedian triangle">automedian triangle</a> is one whose <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Median_(geometry)" title=3D"Median (geometry)">=
medians</a> are in the same proportions as its sides (though in a different=
 order). If <i>ABC</i> is an automedian triangle in which vertex <i>A</i> s=
tands opposite the side <i>a</i>, <i>G</i> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Centroid" title=3D"Centroid">centroid</a> (where the three =
medians of <i>ABC</i> intersect), and <i>AL</i> is one of the extended medi=
ans of <i>ABC</i> with <i>L</i> lying on the circumcircle of <i>ABC</i>, th=
en <i>BGCL</i> is a parallelogram.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Varignon_parallelogram">Var=
ignon parallelogram</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DParallelogram&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit sec=
tion: Varignon parallelogram"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Varignon%27s_theorem=
" title=3D"Varignon's theorem">Varignon's theorem</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Varignon_parallelogram.svg" class=3D"mw-file-=
description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thu=
mb/b/b8/Varignon_parallelogram.svg/250px-Varignon_parallelogram.svg.png" de=
coding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"333" class=3D"mw-file-element" dat=
a-file-width=3D"512" data-file-height=3D"683"></a><figcaption>Proof without=
 words of Varignon's theorem </figcaption></figure>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Varignon%27s_theorem" title=3D"=
Varignon's theorem">Varignon's theorem</a> holds that the <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Midpoint" title=3D"Midpoint">midpoints</a> of the s=
ides of an arbitrary quadrilateral are the vertices of a parallelogram, cal=
led its <i>Varignon parallelogram</i>. If the quadrilateral is <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convex_polygon" title=3D"Convex polygon">conve=
x</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Concave_polygon" title=3D=
"Concave polygon">concave</a> (that is, not self-intersecting), then the ar=
ea of the Varignon parallelogram is half the area of the quadrilateral.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proof_without_words" title=
=3D"Proof without words">Proof without words</a> (see figure):
</p>
<ol><li>An arbitrary quadrilateral and its diagonals.</li>
<li>Bases of similar triangles are parallel to the blue diagonal.</li>
<li>Ditto for the red diagonal.</li>
<li>The base pairs form a parallelogram with half the area of the quadrilat=
eral, <i>A<sub>q</sub></i>, as the sum of the areas of the four large trian=
gles, <i>A<sub>l</sub></i> is 2 <i>A<sub>q</sub></i> (each of the two pairs=
 reconstructs the quadrilateral) while that of the small triangles, <i>A<su=
b>s</sub></i> is a quarter of <i>A<sub>l</sub></i> (half linear dimensions =
yields quarter area), and the area of the parallelogram is <i>A<sub>q</sub>=
</i> minus <i>A<sub>s</sub></i>.</li></ol>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Tangent_parallelogram_of_an=
_ellipse">Tangent parallelogram of an ellipse</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsec=
tion"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DParallelogram&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;secti=
on=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: Tangent parallelogram of an ellipse"><span>=
edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>For an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ellipse" title=3D"Ellips=
e">ellipse</a>, two diameters are said to be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Conjugate_diameters" title=3D"Conjugate diameters">conjugate</a>=
 if and only if the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tangent_line" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Tangent line">tangent line</a> to the ellips=
e at an endpoint of one diameter is parallel to the other diameter. Each pa=
ir of conjugate diameters of an ellipse has a corresponding <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tangent_parallelogram" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Tangent parallelogram">tangent parallelogram</a>, sometimes called a b=
ounding parallelogram, formed by the tangent lines to the ellipse at the fo=
ur endpoints of the conjugate diameters. All tangent parallelograms for a g=
iven ellipse have the same area.
</p><p>It is possible to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Compass_a=
nd_straightedge_constructions" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Compass and s=
traightedge constructions">reconstruct</a> an ellipse from any pair of conj=
ugate diameters, or from any tangent parallelogram.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Faces_of_a_parallelepiped">=
